<P>When dinner was over, we walked in the garden, and I shewed the captain what improvements I had designed to make. He ap|proved of every thing I said, and informed me that he heard from Mirza, the eunuch, my abhorrence of women. But he advised me to keep my sentiments secret, for when you abjure, said he, the Moorish women will make you feel their resentment. But 'tis <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">d continued he, that one of your youth and make should take such an aversion <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the female sex. I told him I had very good reasons for my hatred, and even my mother was odious to me, tho' <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> brought me into the world. Well, but, added the captain, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and a fair face may make great alterations. I told him I was very well assured I should carry my resentment to the grave. I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> he, I have a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> English woman, a slave of mine, that I have lately taken, would make you change your sentiments if you saw her. Sir, answered I. I would be glad to stand the trial to convince you to the contrary, though I would as soon look upon a serpent with my will. Well, said he, I have not learned the strictness of the Moo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s, in keeping women without being seen; or if I had, your aversion to them would convince me I had not much to fear. He desired me to walk a while in the garden, and he would be with me again immediately. Upon this he left me, and went into the house, and returned in five minutes. Come, said he, I have ordered my women to walk in the garden, and you and I will abscond behind these laurels, where we may see them and not be seen. We had not sat long before we could perceive three women <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> us. The two first were very hand|s